Junonia evarete is a butterfly species of the family Nymphalidae.
It features a wingspan of 4-5 inches and has a distinct brown, yellow, and blue coloration.
The forewings of Junonia evarete have distinctive eye-like spots, while the hindwings have a pattern of lines and dashes.
The body of the butterfly is covered in short, dense hairs and has a small head with long antennae.
Junonia evarete can be found in the southern US, Mexico and the Caribbean islands, inhabiting open areas such as meadows, fields and gardens.
The butterfly feeds on nectar from a variety of flowers, including Lantana and Verbena.
Junonia evarete is considered a common and widespread butterfly in its range, but habitat loss and fragmentation are potential threats to its populations.
